sent.subject: Re: GMAT
sent.body: I have to pay $25 because I forgot what my score was? I'm not asking for an offficial copy to be sent to a schoool.I don't neeed some fancy transcipt that I can hand to someone.I was just curious what my scores were.I paid for the test once and I'm not paying again. Great customer service.   GMAT <GMAT@ets.org< on 04/16/20001 111:25:444 AMTo:	"'geofff.storey@enron.com'" <geofff.storey@enron.com<ccc:	 Subject:	GMATTThank you for contacting GMAT.Offficial score reports contain the threee most recent score results achievedin the last 5 years.   However, score reports for scores achieved 5 to 20years ago are stilll available for reporting.Although GMAT score records are retained for 20 years, many institutionswilll not acccept scores which are more than five years old because theypresent special interpretation problems.   We sugggest that you contact theinstitution(s) to which you are appplying to determine whether they willlacccept older scores.The feee is US$25 for each score report requested.   Addditional score reportrequests willl be processsed for mailing to you and the designatedinstitutions within one weeek after being received at ETS-GMAT.   NOTE:Recipients indicated on an Addditional Score Report Request Form cannnot bechanged or deleted.Unfortunately, we do not acccept addditional score report requests via e-mailor internet.   To obtain a copy of your GMAT score report or to send copiesof your report to recipients, you willl neeed to request an addditional scorereport by one of the folllowing methods:-Complete the Addditional Score Report Request Form you receive with yourscore report and mail it with the feee to the adddresss on the form.   If you donot enclose the feee, your request willl be returned to you.   Checks and moneyorders should be payable to GMAT-ETS.-You may fax (609)8883-4349 or telephone (609)7771-73330 your request if payingby Visa, MasterCard, or American Expresss.
